{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}} {{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Daniel v. Waters |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] |CourtSeal=US-CourtOfAppeals-6thCircuit-Seal.png |ArgueDate= |ArgueYear= |DecideDate=April 10, |DecideYear=1975 |FullName=Joseph C. Daniel, Jr., et al., v. Hugh Waters, Chairman, Textbook Commission of the State of Tennessee, et al. |Citations=[[Case citation|515]] [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/515/485/292800/ 485] (6th Cir. 1975) |Prior=[[M.D. Tenn.|District Court]] entered order abstaining from a decision on the merits, February 26, 1974. |Subsequent=On remand, 399 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/399/510/1489371/ 510] ([[M.D. Tenn.]] 1975) |Holding= |Judges=[[George Clifton Edwards, Jr.]], [[Anthony J. Celebrezze]], [[Pierce Lively]] |Majority=Edwards |JoinMajority=Lively |Dissent=Celebrezze |LawsApplied= [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. I]] }}
'''''Daniel v. Waters''''', [[Case citation|515]] [[F.2d]] 485 (6th Cir. 1975)<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Daniel v. Waters |vol=515 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=485 |pinpoint= |court=6th Cir. |date=1975 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/515/485/292800/ |accessdate=2017-12-16 |quote=}}</ref> was a 1975 legal case in which the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] struck down [[Tennessee]]'s law regarding the teaching of "equal time" of [[evolution]] and [[creationism]] in [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] [[science]] classes because it violated the [[Establishment clause]] of the [[US Constitution]].
The plaintiffs were school teachers supported by the [[National Association of Biology Teachers]].
==Background== Various state laws prohibiting the teaching of evolution had been introduced during the 1920s. These laws were challenged in 1968 in the case ''[[Epperson v. Arkansas]]'', which established that such laws were to be held in violation of the constitutional [[separation of Church and State]].<ref>{{ussc|name=Epperson v. Arkansas|link=|volume=393|page=97|pin=|year=1968}}.</ref> The creationist movement reacted to the decision by turning to the promotion of the teaching of creationism in school science classes as equal to evolutionary theory.<ref name=lenny>[http://www.talkreason.org/articles/HistoryID.cfm Creationism/ID, A Short Legal History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140823063247/http://www.talkreason.org/articles/HistoryID.cfm |date=2014-08-23 }} By Lenny Flank, Talk Reason</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2016}}
==The act== The Tennessee law stated, "Any biology textbook used for teaching in the public schools, which expresses an opinion of, or relates a theory about origins or creation of man and his world shall [give] . . . an equal amount of emphasis on . . . the Genesis account in the Bible." (Public Acts of Tennessee, 1973, Chapter 377, cited in LaFollette, 1983, p.&nbsp;80)<ref name=lenny/>
==The ruling== The Federal District Court ruling was that the Tennessee law was "a clearly defined preferential position for the Biblical version of creation as opposed to any account of the development of man based on scientific research and reasoning. For a state to seek to enforce such preference by law is to seek to accomplish the very establishment of religion which the First Amendment to the Constitution of the United States squarely forbids." <ref>''Daniel v Waters'', 515 F.2d at 489.</ref><ref name=lenny/>
==Effect of the ruling== The ruling did not prevent the Bible from being taught in public schools in an appropriate way. The Court stated (quoting from a prior decision): "While study of religions and of the Bible from a literary and historic viewpoint, presented objectively as part of a secular program of education, need not collide with the First Amendment's prohibition, the State may not adopt programs or practices in its public schools or colleges which "aid or oppose" any religion."<ref>{{ussc|name=Abington School District v. Schempp|link=|volume=374|page=203|pin=|year=1963}}.</ref>
Following this ruling, several states then passed new legislation which required that [[creation science]] be given equal time with teaching of evolution. This came to court as ''[[McLean v. Arkansas]]'' (1982), which resulted in a detailed ruling that it was similarly unconstitutional to teach this in public school science classes.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=McLean v. Arkansas |vol=529 |reporter=F. Supp. |opinion=1255 |pinpoint=1258-1264 |court=E.D Ark. |date=1982 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/529/1255/2354824/ |accessdate=2017-12-16 |quote=}}</ref> This was a District level ruling and, while setting a [[persuasive precedent]], it was only a [[binding precedent]] in the relevant district. It was not until ''[[Edwards v. Aguillard]]'' (1987), a similar case in Louisiana, was appealed to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] that creation science was ruled unconstitutional at the federal level,<ref>{{ussc|name=Edwards v. Aguillard|link=|volume=482|page=578 |pin=|year=1987}}.</ref> which resulted in its removal from public school science classes nationwide. The reaction from the creationist forces would be to create the new concept of [[intelligent design]] specifically in order to circumvent this ruling.<ref name=lenny/>
