The '''Debtors (Scotland) Act 1838''' (1 & 2 Vict. c. 114), sometimes the '''Personal Diligence Act''', was an [[Act of Parliament]] in the [[United Kingdom]], signed into law on 16 August 1838. It amended the [[Scots law|law]] of [[Scotland]] in matters relating to personal [[Diligence (Scots law)|diligence]] - the ways in which the person or property of a debtor could be secured - arrestments and poindings (pronounced '''pindings'''). The effect was to simplify the form of proceedings and reduce their expense.

