{{Infobox person | name = Soraya Darabi | image = Soraya Darabi.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Soraya Darabi, Editor of Teacher's Pen Weekly Paper (هفته نامه قلم معلم) and ex-vice president of ITTA | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|9|23}} | baptism_date = | birth_place = [[Ahvaz]], [[Iran]] | residence = | nationality = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = Bachelor in Persian language literature | alma_mater = | occupation = Teacher, journalist, trade union and women rights activist | known_for = | notable_works = Editor of Teacher's Pen Weekly Paper (هفته نامه قلم معلم); ex-vice president of ITTA | movement = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | criminal_charge = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources --> | criminal_penalty = | criminal_status = | spouse = [[Mohammad Khaksari]] | children = [[Sajjad Khaksari]], Sadid Khaksari and Ali Khaksari | parents = Ghodratali Darabi and Marzieh Fatahi | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | website = | footnotes = | box_width = }} '''Soraya Darabi''' ({{lang-fa|{{big| ثریا دارابی}}}} ‘’Soraya Darabi’’; born 23 September 1955) is an Iranian [[teacher]], [[journalist]] and [[trade union]] activist.<ref>[http://www.refworld.org/docid/4b9e52ebc.html UNHCR 2009 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices - Iran]</ref> Moreover, she was editor of Teacher's Pen Weekly Paper and vice president of the [[Iran Teachers Trade Association]] (ITTA).
==Union activities== Soraya Darabi was vice president of the Iran Teachers Trade Association (ITTA)<ref>[http://lib.ohchr.org/HRBodies/UPR/Documents/Session7/IR/EI_UPR_IRN_S07_2010_EducationInternational.pdf Education International – UPR Submission – Iran; Page 3-4]</ref> and she was editor of Teacher's Pen Weekly Paper (هفته نامه قلم معلم) on May 9, 2007 when the Iranian security guards attacked teachers gathering in Tehran (in front of Iranian Islamic Parliament) and arrested 22 teachers.<ref>[http://www.iransos.com/Menschenrechtsverlezung/May07.htm IranSoS Report May 2007, Section 105]</ref><ref>[http://www.iransos.com/Menschenrechtsverlezung/May07.htm Iranian Women's Rights-2007]</ref>
Soraya Darabi was one of female teachers who were arrested.<ref>[https://www.sssup.it/UploadDocs/18078_7_S_Statement_by_700_Advocates_of_Equal_Rights_on_the_Occasion_of_June_12th__The_Day_of_Solidarity_of_Iranian_Women_Iran_Human_Rights_Library_13.pdf STATEMENT BY 700 ADVOCATES OF EQUAL RIGHTS]</ref> By [[Islamic Revolutionary Court]]’s decision, she was detained in [[Evin]] prison for 10 days before her release in exchange for $40,000 in bail.<ref>[http://www.ilo.org/dyn/normlex/en/f?p=NORMLEXPUB:50002:0::NO::P50002_COMPLAINT_TEXT_ID:2910781 Annex 25 of ILO Report No 351, November 2008]</ref> Additionally, since November 5, 2007, Soraya Darabi worked with [[Shirin Ebadi]] as a member of [http://mothersofpeace-iran.com Iranian Mothers of Peace] ([[Persian language|Persian]]: ‘’’’[[:fa:مادران صلح|Madarane Solhe]]’’’’ or مادران صلح) and before the shutdown of [[Defenders of Human Rights Center]] (DHRC) offices during the governance of [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]].
==Personal life== She is the wife of Mohammad Khaksari and mother of Sajjad Khaksari.<ref>[http://www.ei-ie.org/asiapacific/en/newsshow.php?id=1223&theme=rights&country=Iran Education International News, January 2009]</ref><ref>[http://www.amnesty.nl/nieuwsportaal/pers/iran-ensure-free-presidential-election Amnesty Netherland]</ref><ref>[https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2009/nea/136068.htm U.S. Department of State 2009 Human Rights Report: Iran]</ref><ref>[http://rahaizantv.blogspot.it/2009/05/rahai-zan-tv-mino-hemati-interviews.html Rahai Zan TV: Interviews Soraya Darabi]</ref>
